diagnoses.name: Asthma
diagnoses.description: Asthma is a condition in which your airways narrow and swell and may produce extra mucus. This can make breathing difficult and trigger coughing, wheezing, and shortness of breath.

diagnoses.name: Sjogren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Sjogren's syndrome is an immune system disorder characterized by dry eyes and dry mouth. It often accompanies other immune system disorders, such as rheumatoid arthritis and lupus.

diagnoses.name: Endometriosis
diagnoses.description: Endometriosis is an often painful disorder in which tissue similar to the lining inside the uterus — the endometrium — grows outside the uterus. It can cause dysmenorrhea and bloating.

diagnoses.name: Irritable Bowel Syndrome (IBS)
diagnoses.description: Irritable bowel syndrome (IBS) is a common disorder that affects the large intestine. Symptoms include cramping, abdominal pain, bloating, gas, and diarrhea or constipation, or both.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: Lymphoma is a cancer of the lymphatic system, which is part of your immune system. It can cause lymphadenopathy, or swollen lymph nodes.

diagnoses.name: Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)
diagnoses.description: PCOS is a hormonal disorder common among women of reproductive age. Women with PCOS may have infrequent or prolonged menstrual periods or excess male hormone levels. Symptoms can include bloating and dysmenorrhea.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD)
diagnoses.description: COPD is a chronic inflammatory lung disease that causes obstructed airflow from the lungs. Symptoms include breathing difficulty, cough, mucus (sputum) production, and wheezing.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) damages your immune system by destroying the white blood cells that fight infection. Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome (AIDS) is the stage of infection with HIV. It can cause lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD)
diagnoses.description: GERD occurs when stomach acid frequently flows back into the tube connecting your mouth and stomach (esophagus). This acid reflux can cause a chronic cough or wheezing.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: SLE is an autoimmune disease in which the body's immune system mistakenly attacks its own tissues. It can affect the skin, joints, kidneys, brain, and other organs. Symptoms may include lymphadenopathy and dry eyes.
Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.rationale: Hyperglycemia is a hallmark sign of diabetes mellitus. This condition can also contribute to dysautonomias due to its impact on the autonomic nervous system over time.

diagnoses.description: Marfan Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: This genetic disorder affects connective tissue and can lead to aneurysms, particularly in the aorta, and may also cause skeletal manifestations that can contribute to chronic back pain.

diagnoses.description: Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: A group of disorders that affect connective tissues, supporting the skin, bones, blood vessels, and many other organs and tissues. It might be associated with dysautonomia, and aneurysms, and may contribute to chronic back pain due to joint hypermobility and instability.

diagnoses.description: Neurofibromatosis
diagnoses.rationale: This genetic disorder causes tumors to form on nerve tissue. These might cause neurologic symptoms contributing to dysautonomias, chronic pain, and skin manifestations such as warts.

diagnoses.description: Lupus
diagnoses.rationale: A chronic autoimmune disease that can cause widespread inflammation and tissue damage in the affected organs, including the skin (warts-like lesions), kidneys (which can affect glucose control and cause hyperglycemia), and cardiovascular system (aneurysms).

diagnoses.description: Human Papillomavirus (HPV)
diagnoses.rationale: Primarily causes warts, but chronic infection and its systemic effects can indirectly influence other conditions.

diagnoses.description: Immunodeficiency Disorders
diagnoses.rationale: Conditions that compromise the body's immune response can lead to frequent infections, including those causing warts, and more severe complications of common diseases.

diagnoses.description: Peripheral Neuropathy
diagnoses.rationale: While typically a secondary diagnosis to systemic diseases such as diabetes, it can cause dysautonomias and contribute to chronic back pain through nerve damage.

diagnoses.description: Syphilis
diagnoses.rationale: A late-stage manifestation of this sexually transmitted infection can include chronic pain, skin growths similar to warts, and potentially hyperglycemia through systemic illness.

diagnoses.description: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.rationale: A disease where the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. MS can cause a wide range of symptoms, including those related to autonomic dysfunction and chronic pain.

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests

diagnoses.name: Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome (POTS)
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by a significant increase in heart rate upon standing. Symptoms include lightheadedness, fainting, and rapid heartbeat, which may overlap with some of your described symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout your body. Symptoms can include mouth sores, genital sores (ulcers), skin problems, and eye inflammation, as well as vascular symptoms that may mimic POTS.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An immune system disorder characterized by dry eyes and dry mouth, but it can also cause vaginal dryness (contributing to vaginitis) and systemic symptoms that could overlap with your described symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can affect any part of the body, SLE can cause a wide range of symptoms including skin rash (flushing), joint pain, and cardiovascular abnormalities similar to POTS.

diagnoses.name: Rosacea
diagnoses.description: A chronic skin condition that causes redness and visible blood vessels in your face (flushing). It can also cause dry eyes and ocular irritation, potentially linked with blepharospasm.

diagnoses.name: Multiple System Atrophy (MSA)
diagnoses.description: A rare, progressive neurodegenerative disorder that affects your body's autonomic functions (like blood pressure), leading to symptoms similar to POTS. It can also contribute to bladder and sexual dysfunction.

diagnoses.name: Erythromelalgia
diagnoses.description: A rare condition characterized by burning pain, warmth, and redness in the extremities. The symptoms can overlap with flushing and might occur alongside other systemic issues.

diagnoses.name: Mast Cell Activation Syndrome (MCAS)
diagnoses.description: A condition in which mast cells inappropriately release chemical mediators, leading to a wide range of symptoms including flushing, tachycardia, and potentially contributing to gastrointestinal ulcers.

diagnoses.name: Crohn's Disease
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory bowel disease that can cause ulcers throughout the digestive tract including the genital area, potentially contributing to vaginitis. Crohn's can also cause systemic symptoms like fatigue which may overlap with POTS symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory, and mood issues. Some patients report overlapping symptoms with POTS and other autonomic dysfunctions.

Infectious Diseases (e.g., Human Papillomavirus-associated cancers, HIV/AIDS)
Chronic Pain Syndromes (e.g., Fibromyalgia, Chronic Pelvic Pain)

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests

diagnoses.name: Behcet's Disease
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disorder causing ulcers in the mouth and other parts of the body, along with various skin rashes and potentially serious eye inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Erythema Multiforme
diagnoses.description: An immune-mediated condition that can cause ulcers in the mouth and skin lesions, often in reaction to infections or medications.

diagnoses.name: Reiter’s Syndrome (Reactive Arthritis)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune condition that can lead to inflammation of the eyes, urethra, and skin, causing symptoms such as mouth ulcers and skin rashes.

diagnoses.name: Crohn’s Disease
diagnoses.description: A type of inflammatory bowel disease that can cause ulcers throughout the digestive tract, including the mouth, and lead to skin complications.

diagnoses.name: Celiac Disease
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder where the ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine, potentially causing mouth ulcers and dermatitis herpetiformis, a blistering, itchy skin rash.

diagnoses.name: Lichen Planus
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory condition affecting the skin and mucous membranes, leading to mouth ulcers, skin rashes, and possibly involving the gums (desquamative gingivitis).

diagnoses.name: Pemphigus Vulgaris
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that causes painful blisters and sores on the skin and mucous membranes, including the mouth and gums.

diagnoses.name: Psoriasis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that can cause a condition known as psoriatic arthritis and affect the skin, leading to plaque formation and sometimes pustular lesions resembling dyshidrotic eczema.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin Deficiencies
diagnoses.description: Deficiencies in certain vitamins, such as vitamin B12, zinc, folic acid, and iron, can lead to mouth ulcers and potentially affect the skin.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that attacks the glands that provide lubrication to the eyes and mouth, potentially leading to mouth ulcers due to dryness and associated complications.

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests

diagnoses.name: Turner Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Turner syndrome, a condition that affects only females, results when one of the X chromosomes is missing or partially missing. It can cause a variety of medical and developmental problems, including short stature, delayed puberty, infertility, heart defects, and certain learning disabilities.

diagnoses.name: Ataxia-telangiectasia
diagnoses.description: Ataxia-telangiectasia is a rare inherited disorder that affects the nervous system, immune system, and other body systems. This condition is characterized by progressive difficulty with coordinating movements (ataxia), telangiectasias, immune deficiencies, and a higher risk of developing cancers.

diagnoses.name: Usher Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Usher syndrome is a relatively rare genetic disorder that is a leading cause of deafness and gradual vision loss. It is characterized by hearing impairment and retinitis pigmentosa, an eye disorder that affects the retina and causes the progressive loss of vision.

diagnoses.name: Klinefelter Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Klinefelter Syndrome is a genetic condition that affects males. It usually occurs when a boy is born with one or more extra X chromosomes. Symptoms may include delayed puberty, infertility, taller than average height, reduced muscle mass, and reduced facial and body hair.

diagnoses.name: Fabry Disease
diagnoses.description: Fabry disease is a rare genetic disorder caused by the build-up of a particular type of fat, called globotriaosylceramide, in the body’s cells. It's a progressive condition that can lead to a wide range of symptoms, including pain, hearing loss, kidney failure, heart disease, and stroke.

diagnoses.name: McCune-Albright Syndrome
diagnoses.description: McCune-Albright syndrome is a complex genetic disorder affecting the bone, skin, and endocrine system. Characteristics of the syndrome may include fibrous dysplasia of bone, patches of abnormal skin pigmentation, and endocrine problems such as precocious puberty in girls, hyperthyroidism, and growth hormone excess.

diagnoses.name: Noonan Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Noonan syndrome is a genetic disorder that prevents normal development in various parts of the body. A person can be affected by Noonan syndrome in various ways. These may include unusual facial characteristics, short stature, heart defects, other physical problems, and possible developmental delays.

diagnoses.name: Alport Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Alport Syndrome is a genetic condition characterized by kidney disease, hearing loss, and eye abnormalities. It is caused by mutations in the genes involved in the production of collagen, which affects the filtering membranes in the kidneys as well as certain structures in the eyes and the inner ears.

diagnoses.name: Renal Tubular Acidosis
diagnoses.description: Renal Tubular Acidosis (RTA) is a disease that occurs when the kidneys fail to excrete acids into the urine, causing a person's blood to remain too acidic. Over time, RTA can affect the body’s bone and muscle, lead to kidney stones, and may even result in stunted growth in children.

diagnoses.name: Hypogonadotropic Hypogonadism
diagnoses.description: Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism is a condition indicative of delayed or absent puberty. It is often a result of decreased secretion of gonadotropins from the pituitary gland, affecting normal sexual development and fertility.
Hereditary angioedema
diagnoses.details: A rare, genetic disorder causing severe swelling, notably the delayed puberty could indicate a secondary effect of a chronic condition.

diagnoses.description: Chronic kidney disease
diagnoses.details: Can lead to hypertension, changes in electrolyte and fluid balance affecting puberty, and can impact immunoglobulin levels.

diagnoses.description: Primary immunodeficiency disorder
diagnoses.details: Characterized by increased immunoglobulins in some types, can indirectly affect growth and development leading to delayed puberty.

diagnoses.description: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.details: A common cause of delayed puberty. Hypothyroidism can also indirectly contribute to hypertension and has been associated with angioedema.

diagnoses.description: Acromegaly
diagnoses.details: Though typically associated with excessive growth, dysregulated growth hormone can contribute to delayed puberty, hypertension, and has potential implications for immunoglobulin levels.

diagnoses.description: Cushing's syndrome
diagnoses.details: Can cause hypertension, affect growth and development (potentially affecting puberty timing), and alter immune function.

diagnoses.description: Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.details: A chronic autoimmune disease that can cause increased immunoglobulins, hypertension, and has been related to angioedema.

diagnoses.description: Renal artery stenosis
diagnoses.details: Can cause secondary hypertension and might indirectly affect puberty through effects on renal function.

diagnoses.description: Multiple endocrine neoplasia (MEN) syndromes
diagnoses.details: Rare, genetic conditions affecting endocrine glands; could explain a combination of symptoms including hypertension and abnormalities in growth or development.

diagnoses.description: Turner syndrome
diagnoses.details: Although more common in females, chromosomal disorders like Turner syndrome could theoretically account for delayed puberty and could also contribute to hypertension and immune system dysregulation.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's disease
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disorder affecting multiple parts of the body, including the blood vessels. This condition can cause mouth and genital ulcers, skin problems, and may affect the eyes.

diagnoses.name: Crohn's disease
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory bowel disease that affects the lining of the digestive tract, which can lead to ulcers and may also cause complications outside the gastrointestinal tract.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatic fever
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that can develop as a complication of inadequately treated strep throat or scarlet fever. It can cause a variety of symptoms including palpitations due to heart involvement.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that attacks the glands that provide lubrication to the eyes and mouth, causing dryness, but it can also affect other parts of the body leading to more systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: A systemic autoimmune disease that can affect many parts of the body, including joints, skin, kidneys, heart, lungs, blood vessels, and brain. Symptoms can include ulcers and palpitations.

diagnoses.name: Lichen planus
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory condition that can affect the skin and mucous membranes, resulting in purple bumps, itchy skin, and white lacy patches or ulcers in the mouth (oral lichen planus).

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) damages the immune system and weakens the body's ability to fight infections and disease. AIDS is the most advanced stage of HIV infection, which can cause various symptoms throughout the body.

diagnoses.name: Syphilis
diagnoses.description: A bacterial infection usually spread by sexual contact that starts as a painless sore. Secondary syphilis can present with rashes and mucosal ulcers.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that affects multiple organs in the body, most commonly the lungs and lymph glands. It can cause a wide range of symptoms, including fatigue, skin issues, and eye problems.

diagnoses.name: Iron deficiency anemia
diagnoses.description: Anemia caused by a lack of iron in the body, leading to a reduced number of red blood cells. This can cause fatigue, weakness, and in some cases, palpitations.

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests

diagnoses: Rheumatoid Arthritis with secondary Sjögren's syndrome
Angioedema (as part of an allergic reaction)
Malignant neoplasm of the head and neck

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that often presents with dry eyes and dry mouth, which could explain the fibrosis (due to glandular damage), lymphadenitis from immune system activation, mood lability from systemic effects or chronic discomfort, and blepharospasm as a response to dry eyes.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: Another autoimmune disorder that can cause fibrosis in the lungs, lymphadenitis, mood changes, and can also be associated with Sjögren's Syndrome, thus explaining the dry eyes and potentially the blepharospasm.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A systemic autoimmune disease that can cause a wide range of symptoms, including those listed. It can cause lymphadenitis, fibrosis in various organs including the lungs, mood lability, and dry eyes (secondary to Sjögren's syndrome which can co-occur).

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that commonly affects the lungs and lymph nodes, causing fibrosis and lymphadenitis. Dry eyes and mood lability can be part of the systemic symptoms or secondary effects.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Blepharitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the eyelid which can cause blepharospasm and dry eyes. While less directly connected to fibrosis or lymphadenitis, systemic inflammation or associated conditions could potentially link these symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Graft-versus-host disease (GVHD)
diagnoses.description: A condition that can occur after an allogeneic tissue transplant. It can cause dry eyes, blepharospasm due to ocular GVHD, fibrosis in various organs, lymphadenitis, and mood lability due to systemic illness or medications.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.description: A disease that shares features of several connective tissue diseases like systemic lupus erythematosus, scleroderma, and polymyositis. It can provide a framework for understanding the connection between fibrosis, lymphadenitis, mood changes, and eye symptoms.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: While not an immediate consideration, HIV/AIDS can cause lymphadenitis, mood lability, and more indirectly, conditions such as Sjögren's syndrome leading to dry eyes and potentially blepharospasm.

diagnoses.name: Scleroderma
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that leads to hardening and tightening of the skin and connective tissues. It can cause fibrosis in various organs, including the lungs, and has been associated with secondary Sjögren's syndrome, causing dry eyes and potentially affecting mood.

diagnoses.name: Amyloidosis
diagnoses.description: A condition where protein deposits, called amyloid, build up in organs. It can cause systemic symptoms, including fibrosis, potentially affect lymph nodes, and indirectly lead to dry eyes or mood changes through systemic illness.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition characterized by intense headaches often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to light and sound.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A medical condition that occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, causing brain tissue to be damaged.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in the brain.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that affects the central nervous system, leading to symptoms like fatigue, pain, and muscle weakness.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the protective membranes covering the brain and spinal cord, known collectively as the meninges.

diagnoses.name: Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the brain, often caused by a viral infection.

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess
diagnoses.description: A collection of pus that develops in the brain due to an infection.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a transient ischemic attack is a brief, temporary disruption of blood flow to part of the brain, spinal cord, or retina.

diagnoses.name: Intracerebral Hemorrhage
diagnoses.description: A type of stroke caused by bleeding within the brain tissue itself – a life-threatening type of stroke.

diagnoses.name: Vertebrobasilar Insufficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition resulting from the reduction of blood flow to the back part of the brain, which can lead to symptoms such as dizziness, dysarthria, and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic illness involving your central nervous system. The immune system attacks myelin, which is the protective layer around your nerves, leading to demyelination, affecting how nerves conduct signals.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: Occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Many different types of brain tumors exist. Some brain tumors are noncancerous (benign), and some brain tumors are cancerous (malignant).

diagnoses.name: Neurofibromatosis
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that causes tumors to form on nerve tissue. These tumors can develop anywhere in your nervous system, including your brain, spinal cord, and nerves.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barre Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder in which your body's immune system attacks your nerves. Weakness and tingling in your extremities are usually the first symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of migraine that involves neurological phenomena (aura) like visual disturbances and other symptoms like tinnitus and aphasia preceding or accompanying the headache.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a transient ischemic attack is a brief period of symptoms similar to those in a stroke. It can cause symptoms like paralysis or muscle weakness, typically on one side of the body, slurred speech, and double vision.

diagnoses.name: Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS)
diagnoses.description: Also known as Lou Gehrig's disease, it's a progressive nervous system disease that affects nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord, causing loss of muscle control.

diagnoses.name: Myasthenia Gravis
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune neuromuscular disease that causes weakness in the skeletal muscles, which are responsible for breathing and moving parts of the body, including the arms and legs.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: A tick-borne illness caused by the bacterium Borrelia burgdorferi. In its late stages, it can lead to neurological problems such as aphasia, paresthesia, and facial palsy.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A condition where poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death, causing symptoms such as aphasia, weakness, and headache.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a minibar, a temporary blockage of blood flow to the brain, potentially causing aphasia, weakness, and headache.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in the brain that can lead to various symptoms including aphasia, weakness, and headache.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A type of headache that may present with symptoms such as severe headache, aphasia, and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Intracerebral Hemorrhage
diagnoses.description: Bleeding within the brain tissue itself, which can cause aphasia, weakness, and headache.

diagnoses.name: Subarachnoid Hemorrhage
diagnoses.description: An uncommon type of stroke caused by bleeding on the surface of the brain. It's marked by a sudden, severe headache, possibly accompanied by aphasia and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the brain caused by an infection or an autoimmune response. Symptoms can include headache, aphasia, and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: An infection of the protective membranes covering the brain and spinal cord. It could cause symptoms like headache, confusion, aphasia, and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that affects the brain and spinal cord, causing symptoms such as aphasia, weakness, and headache.

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess
diagnoses.description: A collection of pus that develops in the brain due to an infection, presenting with headache, aphasia, and weakness among other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that affects the brain and spinal cord, causing a range of neurological symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: Abnormal cell growth in the brain, which can cause a variety of neurological symptoms depending on its location.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.description: A lack of vitamin B12 can lead to neurological problems, including tingling, numbness, and problems with coordination.

diagnoses.name: Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS)
diagnoses.description: A neurodegenerative disease that affects nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord, leading to loss of muscle control.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A sudden interruption in the blood supply of the brain, leading to potentially permanent neurological damage.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barre Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder attacking the peripheral nervous system, typically leading to weakness, numbness, and tingling.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms, including phonophobia. It's marked by intense, debilitating headaches.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic Neuroma
diagnoses.description: A benign tumor on the cranial nerve that affects balance and hearing, potentially leading to tinnitus and dizziness.

diagnoses.name: Ménière's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear causing vertigo, tinnitus, hearing loss, and a feeling of fullness or congestion in the ear.

diagnoses.name: Cervical Spondylosis
diagnoses.description: Age-related changes in the vertebrae, discs, and joints of the neck which can press on the spinal cord and nerve roots, leading to neurological symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: This autoimmune disease commonly presents with symptoms such as proteinuria, due to kidney involvement, hemolytic anemia, skin manifestations like annular polycyclic rash, and joint pain or arthropathy.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: While primarily known for causing arthropathy, this autoimmune condition can lead to systemic manifestations including anemia and, less commonly, kidney involvement with proteinuria and skin manifestations.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.rationale: This disease features signs and symptoms of a combination of disorders — including SLE, scleroderma, and polymyositis. It can present with proteinuria, hemolytic anemia, skin changes, and arthropathy.

diagnoses.name: Sjogren's Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: Primarily affecting the exocrine glands, it's less commonly associated with proteinuria and hemolytic anemia but can have cutaneous manifestations and joint symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.rationale: This inflammatory disease can cause a distinctive skin rash that could appear as annular polycyclic and it often presents with muscle weakness. Some patients may also have arthropathy, and it can occasionally affect the kidneys and blood cells.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.rationale: This granulomatous disease can affect multiple organs including the skin, presenting annular polycyclic rashes, kidneys resulting in proteinuria, and joints with arthropathy. Hemolytic anemia is less common but possible.

diagnoses.name: Polyarteritis Nodosa
diagnoses.rationale: This vasculitis can lead to symptoms like skin rashes, kidney involvement with proteinuria, arthritis, and in some cases, hemolytic anemia due to blood vessel inflammation affecting various organs.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Caused by the Borrelia burgdorferi bacterium, it can cause arthritis, erythema migrans which could resemble an annular polycyclic rash, and rarely, hemolytic anemia. Kidney involvement is less common.

diagnoses.name: Hemolytic Uremic Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: While primarily characterized by acute renal failure, hemolytic anemia, and thrombocytopenia, it may occasionally present with skin manifestations and arthritic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Lupus Nephritis
diagnoses.rationale: A specific manifestation of SLE affecting the kidneys, leading to proteinuria. It can be associated with hemolytic anemia, skin rashes including annular polycyclic lesions, and arthropathy as part of the broader lupus spectrum.
